            <summary>In the city archive of Feldkirch, a music inventory of the parish church of St. Nikolaus from 1699 is preserved (A-FKsta, Akt Nr. 269). Some 240 items are entered on the 6 folios of the manuscript. Of these, approximately one third are prints and two thirds are manuscripts. A short list of nine musical instruments and a dozen items for the "Tafl Music" complete the contents of this remarkable source.<lb/>
            The parish church of Feldkirch belonged until 1803 to the diocese of Chur. The town was a stronghold of Catholic reformation, hosting a Capuchin convent from 1605 and a Jesuit school from 1649. This may account for the thriving musical activity testified by the <ref target="http://in-dev.rism.digital/images/feldkirch">inventory</ref>, finished on 1 November 1699. The wording of the title, "à me … renovatus", suggests that there was an older inventory, which was supplanted by the present one. The Kantor signed the inventory with his initials, "M.J.C.Sch.r", Johann Caspar Scherer from Biberach, who in 1694 had applied for the post of preceptor in the town school and was granted citizenship in 1718 (A-FKsta, Akt 1242a; Hs. 18, Ratsprotokolle 1718–20, fol. 21r). This privilege was bound to the compiling of a new inventory, which is unfortunately lost.</summary>
